e` on non-terminal and terminal pages\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 2: Add a byte-budget contract test**\n+\n+Create a mailbox with enough payloads to exceed the intended response budget if emitted in one shot, then assert:\n+- a single response stops early\n+- `has_more = true`\n+- `next_cursor` is present\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 3: Use readiness polling, not fixed sleeps**\n+\n+If the test needs a spawned node:\n+- copy the polling readiness pattern used in `apps/node/tests/signed_replication.rs`\n+- do not add ad hoc `sleep(10ms)` or `sleep(100ms)` startup delays\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 4: Run the new endpoint tests and verify they fail**\n+\n+Run:\n+\n+```bash\n+cargo test -p node --test fetch_pagination\n+```\n+\n+Expected: failures because the fetch endpoint still returns only `payloads` and has no query-driven pagination.\n+\n+## Chunk 2: Mailbox Store Pagination\n+\n+### Task 4: Add paginated mailbox-store primitives keyed by row id\n+\n+**Files:**\n+- Modify: `crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs`\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 1: Introduce explicit paginated result types**\n+\n+Add minimal types like:\n+\n+```rust\n+pub struct FetchPageEntry {\n+    pub row_id: i64,\n+    pub envelope: OuterEnvelope,\n+}\n+\n+pub struct FetchPage {\n+    pub entries: Vec<FetchPageEntry>,\n+    pub has_more: bool,\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Do not add `created_at` to the cursor contract.\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 2: Add the paginated store method**\n+\n+Add:\n+\n+```rust\n+fn fetch_page(\n+    &self,\n+    routing_key: &RoutingKey,\n+    limit: usize,\n+    after: Option<i64>,\n+) -> Result<FetchPage, NodeError>;\n+```\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 3: Implement stable SQL ordering**\n+\n+Use row-id order only:\n+\n+```sql\n+SELECT id, envelope_data\n+FROM mailbox_messages\n+WHERE routing_key = ?\n+  AND expires_at > ?\n+  AND (? IS NULL OR id > ?)\n+ORDER BY id ASC\n+LIMIT ?\n+```\n+\n+Fetch `limit + 1` rows internally to compute `has_more`.\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 4: Preserve malformed-row cleanup**\n+\n+Requirements:\n+- invalid rows are still deleted\n+- delete in bounded chunks as implemented after `#65`\n+- invalid rows do not count as successful page entries\n+- cursor progression still uses the last successfully included row id\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 5: Keep `fetch()` compiling during migration**\n+\n+Use one of these approaches:\n+- temporary wrapper that repeatedly calls `fetch_page(...)`\n+- or migrate all callers in the same patch before removing old behavior\n+\n+Choose the narrower path that minimizes scope.\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 6: Re-run the mailbox-store tests**\n+\n+Run:\n+\n+```bash\n+cargo test -p reme-node-core mailbox_store\n+```\n+\n+Expected: all mailbox-store tests pass, including the new cursor contract coverage.\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 7: Commit the store layer**\n+\n+```bash\n+git add crates/reme-node-core/src/mailbox_store.rs\n+git commit -m \"feat(node-core): add paginated mailbox fetch\"\n+```\n+\n+## Chunk 3: Node API Pagination and Response Budgeting\n+\n+### Task 5: Expose paginated fetch from the node API\n+\n+**Files:**\n+- Modify: `apps/node/src/api.rs`\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 1: Add fetch query parsing**\n+\n+Add a query struct for:\n+- `limit: Option<usize>`\n+- `after: Option<i64>`\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 2: Add explicit server bounds**\n+\n+Add separate constants for:\n+- maximum messages per fetch page\n+- maximum serialized fetch response size in bytes\n+\n+Do not reuse the request-body limit constant for response sizing.\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 3: Update `FetchResponse`**\n+\n+Change the response to:\n+\n+```rust\n+pub struct FetchResponse {\n+    pub payloads: Vec<String>,\n+    pub next_cursor: Option<String>,\n+    pub has_more: bool,\n+}\n+```\n+\n+- [ ] **Step 4: Assemble the page with both count and byte limits**\n+\n+The handler should:\n+- call `fetch_page(...)`\n+- encode entries oldest-first\n+- stop before exceeding the configured response byte budget\n+- compute `next_cursor` from the last included row id\n+- set `has_more` if the page was truncated by count or byte budget, or if 