          "type": "tool_use",
          "name": "apply_patch",
          "input": "*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /home/leon0399/Projects/reme/README.md\n+# Resilient Messenger\n+\n+`reme` is an outage-resilient, end-to-end encrypted messaging system written in Rust.\n+\n+It currently uses a mailbox-style HTTP transport with stateless MIK-based encryption, durable node storage, tombstones, and tiered delivery orchestration. The current roadmap and protocol notes live in [ROADMAP.md](ROADMAP.md) and [WHITEPAPER.md](WHITEPAPER.md).\n+\n+## Current Status\n+\n+This repository is still in MVP/PoC stage. The HTTP node API is intentionally small and transport-oriented:\n+\n+- request bodies are opaque base64-encoded wire payloads, not application-level JSON messages\n+- fetch responses are oldest-first and paginated by node-owned mailbox row id\n+- some headers and replication semantics are still evolving\n+\n+## Local Development\n+\n+Build everything:\n+\n+```bash\n+cargo build\n+```\n+\n+Run a mailbox node:\n+\n+```bash\n+cargo run --bin node\n+```\n+\n+Run the client:\n+\n+```bash\n+cargo run --bin client\n+```\n+\n+## HTTP Node API\n+\n+Encoding rules:\n+\n+- `routing_key` in the fetch path is URL-safe base64 without padding of the 16-byte routing key\n+- `POST /api/v1/submit` accepts plain-text standard base64 of the binary `WirePayload`\n+- `GET /api/v1/fetch/...` returns JSON, and each `payloads[]` entry is standard base64 of a binary `WirePayload`\n+- `GET /api/v1/identity` uses standard base64 for the challenge query value; use URL encoding when sending it\n+\n+Useful example values:\n+\n+```bash\n+export NODE_URL=\"http://127.0.0.1:3000\"\n+export ROUTING_KEY_B64=\"AQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQEBAQ\"\n+export CHALLENGE_B64=\"AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA=\"\n+export PAYLOAD_B64=\"<base64-encoded-WirePayload>\"\n+```\n+\n+If node auth is enabled, add `-u USER:PASSWORD` to the `curl` examples below.\n+\n+### `GET /api/v1/health`\n+\n+Request:\n+\n+```bash\n+curl \"$NODE_URL/api/v1/health\"\n+```\n+\n+Response:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"status\": \"ok\",\n+  \"version\": \"0.1.0\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+### `GET /api/v1/stats`\n+\n+Request:\n+\n+```bash\n+curl \"$NODE_URL/api/v1/stats\"\n+```\n+\n+Response:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"mailbox_count\": 1,\n+  \"total_messages\": 3,\n+  \"backend\": \"sqlite\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+### `GET /api/v1/identity?challenge=<base64>`\n+\n+Use this to verify a node identity by challenge-response.\n+\n+Request:\n+\n+```bash\n+curl --get \\\n+  --data-urlencode \"challenge=$CHALLENGE_B64\" \\\n+  \"$NODE_URL/api/v1/identity\"\n+```\n+\n+Successful response:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"signature\": \"c2lnbmF0dXJlLWJhc2U2NC1ieXRlcy1oZXJl\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Example error:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"error\": \"Challenge must be exactly 32 bytes, got 12\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+### `POST /api/v1/submit`\n+\n+Submit a message or tombstone as a base64-encoded wire payload.\n+\n+Request:\n+\n+```bash\n+curl \\\n+  -X POST \\\n+  -H \"Content-Type: text/plain\" \\\n+  --data \"$PAYLOAD_B64\" \\\n+  \"$NODE_URL/api/v1/submit\"\n+```\n+\n+Successful response when the node can also decrypt the message:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"status\": \"ok\",\n+  \"ack_secret\": \"MDEyMzQ1Njc4OWFiY2RlZg==\",\n+  \"signature\": \"c2lnbmVkLXJlY2VpcHQtYmFzZTY0LWJ5dGVz\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Successful response when the node only accepted storage/relay:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"status\": \"ok\",\n+  \"signature\": \"c2lnbmVkLXJlY2VpcHQtYmFzZTY0LWJ5dGVz\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Example errors:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"error\": \"Invalid base64 encoding\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"error\": \"Mailbox full\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+### `GET /api/v1/fetch/{routing_key}`\n+\n+Fetch is paginated and returns messages oldest-first by node mailbox insertion order.\n+\n+Supported query parameters:\n+\n+- `limit`: optional positive integer, clamped by the node\n+- `after`: optional positive integer cursor from the previous `next_cursor`\n+\n+First page request:\n+\n+```bash\n+curl \"$NODE_URL/api/v1/fetch/$ROUTING_KEY_B64?limit=2\"\n+```\n+\n+Response:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"payloads\": [\n+    \"<base64-wire-payload-1>\",\n+    \"<base64-wire-payload-2>\"\n+  ],\n+  \"next_cursor\": \"42\",\n+  \"has_more\": true\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Continuation request:\n+\n+```bash\n+curl \"$NODE_URL/api/v1/fetch/$ROUTING_KEY_B64?limit=2&after=42\"\n+```\n+\n+Final page response:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"payloads\": [\n+    \"<base64-wire-payload-3>\"\n+  ],\n+  \"next_cursor\": \"43\",\n+  \"has_more\": false\n+}\n+```\n+\n+Example error:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"error\": \"Invalid after cursor: must be a positive integer\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+### Common Error Shape\n+\n+Most failing requests return:\n+\n+```json\n+{\n+  \"error\": \"<message>\"\n+}\n+```\n+\n+## OpenAPI / Swagger\n+\n+For the current MVP, full OpenAPI or Swagger UI is probably not worth the cost yet.\n+\n+Why:\n+\n+- the interesting contract is mostly binary `WirePayload` semantics wrapped in base64, not rich JSON schemas\n+- the endpoint set is still small enough to document directly in this README\n+- node-to-node signed-header behavior and some transport details are still moving, so generated specs would churn fast\n+\n+What does make sense now:\n+\n+- keep this README accurate with concrete request/response examples\n+- keep endpoint semantics stable enough that future OpenAPI work does not immediately rot\n+\n+When OpenAPI starts making sense:\n+\n+- once the HTTP surface stops moving\n+- once you want third-party integrations or generated clients\n+- once you are ready to document signed headers and auth behavior as part of a stable contract\n+\n+At that point, I would add a small hand-written OpenAPI spec for the operational HTTP surface and keep `submit`/`fetch` payload bodies modeled as opaque strings with examples, rather than pretending they are ordinary JSON application payloads.\n*** End Patch",
