          "type": "tool_use",
          "name": "apply_patch",
          "input": "*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: /tmp/issue-27.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Enable inbound fetching from ephemeral / LAN-discovered nodes **without** falling back to naive exact-key polling.\n+\n+This issue tracks the client / transport-side policy for polling untrusted discovered peers. It is **not** about configured stable peers, and it is **not** about known contacts discovered on LAN whose identity can already be matched against a known `PublicID`.\n+\n+## Current boundary\n+\n+For now, unknown discovered peers should be treated as:\n+\n+- usable for `best_effort` submit / store-and-forward buffering\n+- not eligible for quorum credit\n+- not eligible for replication\n+- **not eligible for exact `/fetch/{routing_key}` polling**\n+\n+That last restriction is the important one. Exact-key polling leaks too much metadata to an untrusted node.\n+\n+## Problem\n+\n+Polling an untrusted ephemeral node with:\n+\n+```http\n+GET /api/v1/fetch/{base64(routing_key)}\n+```\n+\n+reveals:\n+\n+- the exact routing key, which acts as a stable identity fingerprint\n+- polling frequency and online/offline behavior\n+- timing correlations across sessions\n+- IP / network adjacency for a specific identity fingerprint\n+\n+This is acceptable for configured trusted peers, but it is the wrong default for anonymous or pseudonymous discovered relays.\n+\n+## Scope\n+\n+This issue is specifically about:\n+\n+- ephemeral HTTP targets\n+- LAN-discovered peers\n+- untrusted / anonymous / pseudonymous store-and-forward relays\n+\n+This issue is **not** the trusted-peer authn/pinning issue tracked by #68.\n+\n+## Required direction\n+\n+Untrusted discovered peers may only support inbound fetch once the fetch path is privacy-preserving. That means:\n+\n+- no exact-key polling against untrusted discovered peers\n+- use the privacy-preserving fetch path from #32 instead\n+- keep per-target rate limits / poll budgets to bound abuse\n+\n+## Relationship to discovery\n+\n+This issue is what unlocks the second half of the opportunistic LAN relay scenario:\n+\n+1. Alice stores to Charlie on LAN while Bob is offline\n+2. Charlie later moves to Bob's network\n+3. Bob fetches from Charlie without exposing an exact stable routing-key fingerprint\n+\n+Until this issue is solved, scenario 2 is only half-complete:\n+\n+- push / store to unknown discovered peers is allowed\n+- fetch / poll from unknown discovered peers is not\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- transport can represent that an untrusted discovered peer is fetchable only via a privacy-preserving mode\n+- exact-key `/fetch/{routing_key}` polling is not used for untrusted discovered peers\n+- inbound polling from untrusted discovered peers is rate-limited / budgeted\n+- known contacts discovered on LAN remain a separate path and can continue to use identity-verified direct delivery\n+- documentation and UI make the trusted-vs-untrusted polling distinction explicit\n+\n+## Related\n+\n+- #32 is the API / protocol blocker for the privacy-preserving fetch path\n+- #49 may later layer per-recipient policy on top of this\n+- #68 remains scoped to configured / trusted peer authn and pin verification\n*** Add File: /tmp/issue-32.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Enhance the `/fetch` API with a privacy-preserving mode for polling ephemeral / untrusted discovered nodes.\n+\n+This issue is the protocol / API blocker for enabling inbound fetch from anonymous or pseudonymous LAN-discovered relays. Exact-key fetch should remain the path for configured trusted peers; this issue adds a second fetch mode for untrusted peers.\n+\n+Related to #27.\n+\n+## Problem\n+\n+The current fetch route requires an exact 16-byte routing key:\n+\n+```http\n+GET /api/v1/fetch/{base64(routing_key)}\n+```\n+\n+For untrusted discovered nodes, that reveals:\n+\n+- a stable identity fingerprint derived from `PublicID`\n+- online / offline polling behavior\n+- cross-session correlation opportunities\n+\n+That is too much leakage for anonymous or pseudonymous LAN-discovered relays.\n+\n+## Proposed solution\n+\n+Add a privacy-preserving fetch mode based on a prefix plus optional bloom filter:\n+\n+```http\n+GET /api/v1/fetch/{prefix_b64}\n+GET /api/v1/fetch/{prefix_b64}?bloom={filter_b64}&k={count}\n+```\n+\n+### Prefix\n+\n+- required\n+- length: 2-16 bytes\n+- shorter prefix => more privacy, more bandwidth\n+- full 16-byte prefix remains equivalent to today's exact match and should stay reserved for trusted fetch\n+\n+### Bloom filter\n+\n+- optional refinement within the prefix space\n+- allows plausible deniability and multi-key polling\n+- hash count configurable via `k`\n+\n+## Important interaction with bounded fetch\n+\n+The privacy-preserving fetch mode must preserve the response-bounding guarantees added in #67.\n+\n+This means the new API must also be:\n+\n+- paginated / bounded\n+- oldest-first within the matched candidate set\n+- protected by an explicit response-size budget\n+\n+We should not reintroduce oversized fetch responses while trying to improve privacy.\n+\n+## Storage / query changes\n+\n+Add prefix-based lookup support to the mailbox store:\n+\n+```rust\n+trait MessageStore {\n+    fn fetch_by_prefix(...);\n+}\n+```\n+\n+For SQLite, this should use a prefix range query rather than full-table scanning where possible.\n+\n+## Policy goal\n+\n+After this issue lands:\n+\n+- configured trusted peers may continue using exact-key fetch\n+- untrusted discovered peers may use the privacy-preserving fetch mode\n+- exact-key polling remains disabled for untrusted discovered peers\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- `/fetch` supports prefix-based matching with validated prefix lengths\n+- optional bloom filter support is implemented with bounded input sizes\n+- prefix/bloom fetch responses remain paginated and byte-bounded\n+- client transport can use this mode for untrusted discovered peers\n+- exact-key fetch remains available for trusted/configured peers\n+- tests cover privacy-mode matching, continuation correctness, and response-budget enforcement\n+\n+## Open questions\n+\n+1. Should privacy-preserving fetch use a separate route or overload the existing route?\n+2. What default prefix length gives a sane privacy/bandwidth trade-off for LAN discovery?\n+3. What bloom filter size and hash-count limits prevent request-side abuse?\n+\n+## Related\n+\n+- #27 tracks when this capability should be used\n+- #49 may later make the choice per-recipient\n+- #67 already established bounded fetch semantics that this API must preserve\n*** Add File: /tmp/issue-new-discovery-policy.md\n+## Summary\n+\n+Add an explicit capability / trust policy for discovered peers.\n+\n+Discovery gives us an addressable endpoint, not trust. The current model needs a small policy layer so LAN-discovered peers can be used safely without pretending that \"discovered\" means \"trusted\".\n+\n+## Why this matters\n+\n+We have at least three distinct peer classes:\n+\n+1. **Known contact discovered on LAN**\n+   - identity can be matched against a known contact `PublicID`\n+   - usable for direct delivery\n+\n+2. **Unknown discovered relay**\n+   - anonymous / pseudonymous peer discovered dynamically\n+   - useful for opportunistic best-effort store-and-forward\n+   - not equivalent to a configured stable relay\n+\n+3. **Configured trusted peer**\n+   - stable peer with explicit config and optional identity / pin verification\n+   - usable for exact fetch, quorum, and replication\n+\n+Without an explicit policy layer, discovery risks collapsing these into one trust bucket.\n+\n+## Non-goals\n+\n+- This issue does **not** solve trusted-peer authn / pinning for configured peers; that remains #68.\n+- This issue does **not** add privacy-preserving fetch itself; that remains #32 / #27.\n+- This issue does **not** try to distinguish \"client\" from \"node\" as a type system concept.\n+\n+## Required design shape\n+\n+Model policy, not peer type.\n+\n+At minimum, discovered peers need enough metadata to answer:\n+\n+- do we know this peer's identity?\n+- how much do we trust this peer?\n+- which roles is this peer allowed to influence?\n+\n+An implementation may use different types/names, but it needs to express something equivalent to:\n+\n+- identity binding: unknown vs known `PublicID`\n+- trust level: unverified discovered vs verified known identity vs configured trusted\n+- allowed roles: direct send, best-effort store, fetch mode, replicate, quorum credit\n+\n+## Initial policy rules\n+\n+### Known contact discovered on LAN\n+\n+- direct delivery allowed\n+- may bypass quorum as a direct path\n+- identity must match the known contact `PublicID`\n+\n+### Unknown discovered peer\n+\n+- `best_effort` submit / store allowed\n+- no quorum credit\n+- no replication\n+- no exact-key fetch\n+- privacy-preserving fetch may be added later via #32 / #27\n+\n+### Configured trusted peer\n+\n+- existing stable-peer behavior\n+- exact fetch / quorum / replication as configured\n+- trusted-peer authn and pin verification remain governed by #68\n+\n+## Acceptance criteria\n+\n+- discovery outputs carry enough policy metadata to distinguish the three cases above\n+- unknown discovered peers are prevented from accidentally entering trusted fetch / quorum / replication paths\n+- known-contact direct delivery can be enabled without also trusting anonymous relays\n+- tests cover role restrictions for unverified discovered peers\n+- policy is documented in transport / discovery docs\n+\n+## Related\n+\n+- #27 privacy-preserving polling from ephemeral nodes\n+- #32 prefix + bloom filter fetch for untrusted peers\n+- #49 per-recipient delivery policy\n+- #68 configured / trusted peer authn and pin verification\n*** End Patch\n",
