          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "<proposed_plan>\n# mDNS / LAN Discovery Implementation Plan\n\n**Summary**\n\nBuild the full LAN discovery feature as a shared discovery subsystem plus transport/runtime integration for both the client app and standalone node. The feature set includes: mDNS advertisement, browsing, direct delivery to verified known contacts, automatic untrusted LAN relay registration when relay mode is enabled, identity refresh on drift, UI-visible discovered peers, and coordinator-enforced capability policy. It explicitly does **not** enable exact-key fetch from untrusted discovered peers; that remains gated on the privacy-preserving fetch work in `#27` / `#32`.\n\n## Key Changes\n\n### 1. Shared discovery engine\n- Add a new shared crate, `crates/reme-discovery`, so discovery lifecycle, verification, and policy do not get duplicated across `apps/client` and `apps/node`.\n- Define a backend abstraction around mDNS/Bonjour:\n  - `DiscoveryBackend` for advertise / browse / stop\n  - `AdvertisementSpec`\n  - `DiscoveryEvent` (`Found`, `Updated`, `Lost`, `NetworkChanged`)\n  - `DiscoveredPeer` with address, port, TXT metadata, last_seen, and source interface info\n- Define a versioned TXT schema for `_reme._tcp.local`:\n  - `v=1`\n  - `rk=<routing_key_base64url>` when the peer is direct-addressable\n  - `relay=1` when the peer accepts untrusted best-effort relay ingress\n  - `identity=1` when `/api/v1/identity` is available\n- Treat TXT data as hints only. Trust comes from verification and policy, not from advertisement contents.\n\n### 2. Peer classification and capability policy\n- Add a discovery policy model that is more explicit than `TargetKind`:\n  - `IdentityBinding`: `Unknown` or `KnownPublicId(PublicID)`\n  - `TrustLevel`: `UnverifiedDiscovered`, `VerifiedKnownIdentity`, `ConfiguredTrusted`\n  - `PeerCapabilities`: `direct_send`, `best_effort_store`, `exact_fetch`, `replicate`, `grants_quorum_credit`\n- Hard defaults:\n  - verified known contact on LAN: `direct_send=true`\n  - unknown discovered relay with relay mode enabled: `best_effort_store=true`\n  - unknown discovered relay: `exact_fetch=false`, `replicate=false`, `grants_quorum_credit=false`\n- Add config for both client and node:\n  - `lan_discovery.enabled`\n  - `lan_discovery.advertise`\n  - `lan_discovery.browse`\n  - `lan_discovery.refresh_interval_secs` default `300`\n  - `lan_discovery.auto_use_contacts` default `true`\n  - `lan_relay.accept_requests` default `false`\n  - `lan_relay.use_discovered_relays` default `false`\n  - `lan_relay.auto_use_strangers` default `true` once relay use is enabled\n- Prepare, but do not fully implement, future per-contact trust overrides:\n  - contact-level hook for `allow_direct_lan` / `allow_auto_relay`\n  - app event type for “new stranger relay discovered” so later UI can prompt or notify\n- Keep `#27` / `#32` open and referenced from code/docs as the blocker for untrusted-peer fetch.\n\n### 3. Identity verification and refresh\n- Reuse the existing `/api/v1/identity?challenge=` endpoint on both standalone node and embedded client HTTP server.\n- Discovery flow for direct-capable peers:\n  - browse mDNS result\n  - read advertised routing key\n  - narrow known contacts to those whose routing key matches\n  - call `verify_identity()` with those candidate `PublicID`s\n  - if one verifies, bind peer to that contact and promote it to verified direct peer\n- Do not attempt to “verify” anonymous stranger relays beyond transport reachability. For them, stay in untrusted relay mode.\n- Add background refresh:\n  - periodic refresh every configured interval\n  - immediate refresh on direct-delivery failure\n  - refresh on mDNS reannounce/update\n  - remove or downgrade stale direct peers when verification no longer matches\n- Base continuity on identity, not IP address. IP/port changes are expected.\n\n### 4. Transport-layer integration\n- Migrate the client send path from `CompositeTransport` to `TransportCoordinator`.\n- Extend `TransportCoordinator` and `TransportRegistry` so discovered targets are first-class managed entities, not just ad hoc runtime additions:\n  - add explicit add/update/remove APIs for discovered HTTP targets\n  - keep discovered Direct peers in the HTTP pool as ephemeral targets so Tier 1 uses them\n  - keep discovered untrusted relays in a separate BestEffort class so they do not participate in quorum or exact fetch\n- Add a discovery-owned target lifecycle manager:\n  - dedupe by stable peer identity when known, else by discovered service instance + address\n  - update existing target on address change\n  - remove targets when lost/expired\n  - keep registry metadata synchronized with pool/coordinator state\n- Do **not** use unknown discovered relays for inbound polling.\n- Preserve current configured HTTP/MQTT peers as Quorum / BestEffort stable targets.\n\n### 5. Runtime integration\n- `apps/client`\n  - advertise embedded HTTP server when enabled\n  - browse LAN peers in the background\n  - auto-register verified contacts as Direct tier targets\n  - auto-register unknown relays as BestEffort targets only when relay use is enabled\n  - surface discovered peer state in the TUI, including role and trust state\n- `apps/node`\n  - advertise relay capability when configured to accept LAN relay ingress\n  - browse when configured to use discovered relays\n  - auto-register unknown discovered relays as untrusted BestEffort egress candidates\n  - never treat discovered peers as replication peers or quorum peers unless separately configured and trusted\n- Keep standalone nodes and client embedded nodes on the same discovery substrate and policy model.\n\n### 6. Relay behavior\n- Implement the plan against the roadmap’s current relay boundary:\n  - discovered stranger relays may accept/store outbound envelopes for external recipients\n  - they are untrusted and best-effort only\n  - they receive no quorum credit\n  - they are excluded from replication and exact-key fetch\n- The Charlie/Bob pickup scenario remains incomplete until privacy-preserving fetch exists. The plan should leave the relay state model and discovery metadata ready for that later phase, but not fake it now.\n\n## Public Interfaces / Types\n\n- New crate: `reme-discovery`\n- New core types:\n  - `DiscoveryBackend`\n  - `DiscoveryManager`\n  - `AdvertisementSpec`\n  - `DiscoveredPeer`\n  - `DiscoveryEvent`\n  - `IdentityBinding`\n  - `TrustLevel`\n  - `PeerCapabilities`\n- `TransportRegistry` / `TransportCoordinator` additions:\n  - managed discovered-target add/update/remove APIs\n  - separation between discovered Direct targets and discovered untrusted relay targets\n- Config additions in both client and node config trees:\n  - `lan_discovery.*`\n  - `lan_relay.*`\n- UI/domain event addition:\n  - app-level discovered-peer event for future notifications/prompts\n\n## Test Plan\n\n- Unit tests for TXT record encode/decode, peer dedupe, loss/refresh handling, and policy classification.\n- Unit tests for discovery verification:\n  - known contact verifies and becomes Direct\n  - no candidate match stays untrusted\n  - address change with same identity updates existing target\n  - failed refresh removes or downgrades the peer\n- Transport tests:\n  - discovered verified peer is used in Direct tier\n  - discovered unknown relay is only used in BestEffort tier\n  - unknown discovered relay never appears in quorum count\n  - unknown discovered relay is never polled via exact-key fetch\n- Client/node integration tests with a fake discovery backend:\n  - client discovers client and sends direct\n  - client discovers relay-capable node and submits via untrusted relay when relay mode is enabled\n  - relay mode disabled means discovered stranger is visible but unused\n  - discovery loss removes the runtime target\n- End-to-end acceptance scenarios:\n  - two clients on same LAN discover within 5 seconds and direct delivery works\n  - DHCP / IP reassignment is corrected by r