          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a17b********61e5</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********aFND</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/872f27a1-9c0c-45e4-b6a3-3674f486326d/tasks/a17b640b0322761e5.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Review architecture & abstractions\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have all the evidence I need. Here is my review.\n\n---\n\n## Architecture and Abstraction Quality Review\n\n### ARCH-1\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** `reme-discovery` crate has a hidden upward dependency on `reme-transport` for identity verification\n\n**Details:** The plan states that `/api/v1/identity` verification stays in `reme-transport` and \"discovery controllers call into that existing transport-owned logic\" (plan line 35). However, the discovery controllers described in Chunk 3 (lines 99-108) must verify candidate peers via the identity endpoint, match against known contacts (which requires `PublicID` from `reme-identity`), and then register direct targets into `TransportCoordinator`. The plan places these controllers ambiguously -- they consume `DiscoveryEvent` from `reme-discovery` and produce mutations on `TransportCoordinator` from `reme-transport`. The controllers themselves are not assigned to a specific crate. If they live in `reme-discovery`, the crate depends upward on both `reme-transport` (for HTTP identity probes and coordinator mutation) and `reme-identity` (for `PublicID` matching). If they live in the app layer, `reme-discovery` is cleanly low-level, but the plan never states this explicitly.\n\n**Recommendation:** The plan should explicitly state that discovery controllers are app-layer glue (in `apps/client` and `apps/node`), not part of `reme-discovery`. The `reme-discovery` crate should export only backend-agnostic types (`DiscoveryEvent`, `RawDiscoveredPeer`, `AdvertisementSpec`) with no dependency on `reme-transport` or `reme-identity`. Add a dependency diagram to the plan showing the crate DAG: `reme-discovery` at the bottom, controllers in app crates at the top, `reme-transport` and `reme-identity` as siblings.\n\n---\n\n### ARCH-2\n**Severity:** Critical\n**Title:** Transport capability model is described aspirationally but never concretely designed\n\n**Details:** Chunk 2 (lines 90-97) lists three participation categories: \"send-only direct targets,\" \"stable pollable mailbox targets,\" and \"future relay candidates.\" It says the coordinator must become the single source of truth and the registry must stay derived. But the plan never specifies the actual mechanism. Currently, the distinction between what gets polled and what doesn't is hardcoded: `TransportCoordinator::subscribe()` (coordinator.rs:211) polls the entire `http_pool` via `pool.fetch_once()`, and `TransportCoordinator::try_direct_tier()` (coordinator.rs:503) selects ephemeral targets by `TargetKind::Ephemeral`. There is no concept of \"send-only\" -- every `HttpTarget` in the pool is fetchable. The plan does not specify whether \"send-only\" becomes a new `TargetKind` variant, a new field on `TargetConfig`, a separate pool, or a filter predicate on the coordinator's subscribe loop. This is the most structurally impactful change in the plan and it has zero design detail.\n\n**Recommendation:** Chunk 2 needs a concrete type-level specification. Options include: (a) add a `TargetCapabilities` bitflags struct to `TargetConfig` with `SEND`, `FETCH`, `QUORUM_CREDIT`, `REPLICATE` flags; (b) split the HTTP pool into `mailbox_pool` and `direct_pool` inside the coordinator; or (c) add a filter predicate to `subscribe()` that skips non-fetchable targets. The plan should pick one, show the struct/enum changes, and show how `fetch_once` in `pool.rs:602` and the polling loop in `coordinator.rs:251` will honor the new capability.\n\n---\n\n### ARCH-3\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** `TransportCoordinator` has no `remove_target` or `add_target` API, making dynamic discovery impossible\n\n**Details:** The plan requires discovery controllers to \"add/remove only send-only direct targets\" (line 106) and \"stale-peer downgrade/removal\" (line 107). However, `TransportCoordinator` (coordinator.rs) has `set_http_pool()` and `set_mqtt_pool()` but no methods to add or remove individual targets from those pools at runtime. While `TransportPool<T>` does have `add_target()` and `remove_target()` (pool.rs:117-136), the coordinator does not expose these -- it takes ownership of pools at construction time. The plan says the coordinator \"must be the single runtime-side owner of dynamic target state\" (line 95) but never specifies the API surface that would make this possible. Currently the only runtime mutation path is through `TransportRegistry::add_http_target()` (registry.rs:117-147), which adds to the `CompositeTransport` -- exactly the component the plan wants to remove.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a concrete API design for `TransportCoordinator` that includes `add_http_target()`, `remove_http_target()`, and ideally `update_http_target()` methods. These should delegate to the underlying pool's `add_target`/`remove_target` and emit events (for registry synchronization). This is prerequisite work for Chunk 2 and should be called out as a subtask.\n\n---\n\n### ARCH-4\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** `CompositeTransport` to `TransportCoordinator` migration is underspecified -- the types are structurally incompatible\n\n**Details:** The client currently holds `Client<CompositeTransport>` (app.rs:319) where `Client<T: Transport>` is generic over the `Transport` trait. `CompositeTransport` is a `Vec<Arc<dyn Transport>>` with trait-object erasure (composite.rs:41). `TransportCoordinator` is concrete typed: it holds `Option<Arc<TransportPool<HttpTarget>>>` and `Option<Arc<TransportPool<MqttTarget>>>` (coordinator.rs:117-119). The plan says \"replace the client app's CompositeTransport send path with TransportCoordinator\" (line 112) but this is not a drop-in swap. Currently, direct peers are added as `HttpTarget` instances directly into the `CompositeTransport` (app.rs:576), while MQTT transports are added as trait objects. The coordinator cannot accept arbitrary `dyn Transport` -- it needs typed pools. The plan does not address how MQTT targets currently added as trait objects to `CompositeTransport` would be migrated, nor how the `Client<T>` generic would change (to `Client<TransportCoordinator>`? Removing the generic?).\n\n**Recommendation:** Chunk 4 should specify: (a) whether `Client` drops the `<T: Transport>` generic in favor of always using `TransportCoordinator`, (b) how MQTT targets currently in `CompositeTransport` move into the coordinator's `mqtt_pool`, and (c) whether a \"legacy composite\" adapter is needed for the transition period. The plan should acknowledge that direct peers currently bypass pools entirely (they go into composite as trait objects) and spell out the new path (direct peers go into `http_pool` as `Ephemeral` `HttpTarget` instances).\n\n---\n\n### ARCH-5\n**Severity:** Minor\n**Title:** `TargetKind::Ephemeral` already covers mDNS-discovered peers -- the plan implies a new category without acknowledging this\n\n**Details:** The existing `TargetKind` enum (target.rs:158-177) has `Ephemeral` with the doc comment \"discovered peers (DHT, mDNS, Iroh)\" and retry characteristics appropriate for transient peers (1s-10s backoff, max 5 attempts, higher priority). The plan proposes \"send-only direct targets\" as a distinct concept, but discovered verified peers from mDNS are exactly what `Ephemeral` was designed for. The plan's capability model (send-only vs fetch-capable) is orthogonal to the durability model (`Stable` vs `Ephemeral`). The plan does not acknowledge that it is introducing a second classification axis rather than extending the existing one.\n\n**Recommendation:** State explicitly that `TargetKind` remains the durability/retry axis, and a new orthogonal axis (capabilities/participation) is being added. Show how both axes compose -- e.g., a discovered peer is `Ephemeral` + `SendOnly`, while a configured mailbox is `Stable` + `FetchCapable + QuorumCredit`. This prevents future confusion about whether to extend `TargetKind` or the capability model.\n\n---\n\n### ARCH-6\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** Dual-authority problem is identified but not resolved -- Chunk 2 states the desire without a concrete transition design\n\n**Details:** The plan says \"Make TransportCoordinator the single runtime-side owner of dynamic target state after migration; TransportRegistry must stay derived\" (line 95) and \"discovery controllers must mutate one runtime-side source of truth, not both registry and transport independently\" (line 96). However, `TransportRegistry` currently holds its own `Arc<CompositeTransport>` (registry.rs:58) and its own `ephemeral_meta` HashMap (registry.rs:61), and `add_http_target()` (registry.rs:117-147) writes to both independently. The plan does not specify how `TransportRegistry` becomes derived. Does it become a read-only view that queries the coordinator? Does it get replaced entirely by `TransportQuery` on the coordinator? Does `ephemeral_meta` move to the coordinator? The plan names the problem without solving it.\n\n**Recommendation:** Specify the concrete end state for `TransportRegistry`: either (a) it becomes a thin wrapper that delegates all queries to `TransportCoordinator` and holds only display metadata (labels, tier classification), with no transport mutation methods; or (b) it is removed entirely and its enrichment logic moves to a `CoordinatorQuery` trait. The plan should also specify what happens to the `CompositeTransport` reference inside the registry during migration -- does it get dropped, or does it remain as a fallback?\n\n---\n\n### ARCH-7\n**Severity:** Observation\n**Title:** `MessageReceiver` takes `TransportPool<HttpTarget>` directly, creating a parallel receive path to the coordinator\n\n**Details:** `MessageReceiver` (receiver.rs:83-84) takes `Arc<TransportPool<HttpTarget>>` and runs its own polling loop. `TransportCoordinator::subscribe()` (coordinator.rs:206-220) also runs a polling loop over the same `http_pool`. The plan does not mention `MessageReceiver` at all. If the client migrates to the coordinator, the standalone `MessageReceiver` becomes dead code. But if both exist during migration, the same pool could be polled twice. The plan's Chunk 4 should address this.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a note in Chunk 4 that `MessageReceiver` is superseded by `TransportCoordinator::subscribe()` and should be deprecated or removed as part of the migration. Alternatively, if `MessageReceiver` is used by other consumers (e.g., the node app), clarify its continued role.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>76488</total_tokens><tool_uses>13</tool_uses><duration_ms>88617</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/872f27a1-9c0c-45e4-b6a3-3674f486326d/tasks/a17b640b0322761e5.output",
