          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>aae6********644c</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********kbSj</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/872f27a1-9c0c-45e4-b6a3-3674f486326d/tasks/aae66d1624213644c.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Review security & trust model\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have all the evidence I need. Let me produce the structured review.\n\n---\n\n# Security & Trust Model Review: mDNS/LAN Discovery Plan\n\n---\n\n## SEC-1\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** Routing key broadcast enables passive LAN presence detection and cross-session correlation\n\n**Details:** The plan broadcasts `rk=<routing_key_base64url>` in mDNS TXT records. Per `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-identity/src/lib.rs:212-217`, the routing key is `BLAKE3(PublicID)[0..16]` -- a deterministic, stable 16-byte value derived from a user's permanent public key. Any passive observer on the LAN can collect these routing keys over time to build a presence log of which identities are on the network, when they appear/disappear, and which IP addresses they use. Because the routing key is also the mailbox address used in `OuterEnvelope.routing_key` and the `/api/v1/fetch/{routing_key}` path, the broadcast directly reveals the value an attacker would need to poll messages from any relay or mailbox node. The 128-bit space makes brute-force preimage infeasible, but the correlation attack is purely passive and zero-cost.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a section to the plan addressing LAN privacy. Consider one of: (a) rotate the TXT `rk` value using a short-lived, session-specific derivative (e.g., BLAKE3-KDF with a per-boot nonce) that known contacts can resolve but passive observers cannot link across sessions; (b) omit `rk` entirely and rely solely on the identity challenge-response to match peers; (c) at minimum, document the threat and make `rk` advertisement opt-in per contact list rather than always-on. Option (b) eliminates the privacy leak but makes the O(N) verification problem worse (see SEC-2).\n\n---\n\n## SEC-2\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** Identity verification is O(N) in contacts with no timing-attack mitigation, enabling contact-list probing\n\n**Details:** The plan says: \"use advertised `rk` to narrow known contacts, then call `/api/v1/identity?challenge=<base64>`.\" The existing endpoint (both at `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/node/src/api.rs:862-933` and `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/tui/http_server.rs:418-478`) returns only a signature -- never the node's public key. The verifier must try each candidate contact's public key against the signature. If `rk` narrows to one candidate, this is O(1). But if `rk` is removed for privacy (SEC-1), or if multiple contacts share a routing-key collision (improbable at 128 bits but possible with many contacts), the verifier iterates all contacts. More critically, a malicious peer advertising a *valid* `rk` belonging to a real contact forces the verifier to issue the challenge. The attacker cannot sign correctly, but the verifier's attempt-and-fail timing reveals that the verifier has that routing key in its contact list, leaking social graph information.\n\n**Recommendation:** (a) The plan should specify that verification failure must be constant-time with respect to the number of candidates tried -- i.e., always try all candidates before returning a result (or use a fixed delay). (b) Add a note that if `rk`-based narrowing reduces to zero candidates, the identity probe should be skipped entirely (no HTTP request) to avoid revealing interest. (c) Consider a Noise NK or KK handshake variant that proves identity mutually in one round-trip without the O(N) scan.\n\n---\n\n## SEC-3\n**Severity:** Critical\n**Title:** Challenge-response protocol lacks channel binding, enabling MITM relay attacks\n\n**Details:** The signed data is `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || node_pubkey` (per `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-encryption/src/lib.rs:376-383`). The challenge is a client-generated 32-byte random value, and the plan does not specify any binding to the transport session (IP, port, TLS channel binding, or a session ID). A MITM on the LAN can: (1) advertise the same `rk` as a legitimate peer, (2) when challenged, forward the challenge to the real peer's `/api/v1/identity` endpoint, (3) relay the signature back, passing verification. The client then registers the attacker's IP/port as a verified direct target and sends messages to the attacker. Since the identity endpoint is unauthenticated GET over plain HTTP with no TLS requirement specified, this is straightforward.\n\n**Recommendation:** The plan must specify at least one of: (a) TLS with self-signed certificates and certificate pinning (the certificate fingerprint becomes part of the signed data or is verified out-of-band); (b) binding the challenge to the responder's IP:port and the verifier's IP:port in the signed data, so a relayed signature is invalid for a different address pair; (c) a Noise handshake that provides mutual authentication and session key establishment, making MITM detectable. Option (c) is the strongest and most future-proof.\n\n---\n\n## SEC-4\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** Stranger-relay trust restrictions are not enforceable in the current transport code\n\n**Details:** The plan states discovered stranger relays get `grants_quorum_credit=false`, `replicate=false`, etc. However, the current `TransportCoordinator` (`/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/coordinator.rs`) does not have a per-target capability flag system. Quorum counting at lines 611-624 and 735-758 filters by `TargetKind::Stable` vs `TargetKind::Ephemeral` -- there is no third kind for \"stranger relay\" and no `grants_quorum_credit` flag on `TargetConfig` (`/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/target.rs:396-427`). A stranger relay added as any `TargetKind` would either count toward quorum (if `Stable`) or participate in Direct tier (if `Ephemeral`). Chunk 2 of the plan mentions adding capability categories but does not describe the concrete data model or how existing quorum calculation code would be gated.\n\n**Recommendation:** Chunk 2 must be more specific: (a) define a `TargetCapabilities` struct with explicit boolean fields (`can_direct_send`, `can_exact_fetch`, `grants_quorum_credit`, `can_replicate`) on `TargetConfig`; (b) update `quorum_target_count()` and `submit_to_quorum_targets()` to filter on `grants_quorum_credit` rather than on `TargetKind::Stable`; (c) add invariant tests that a target with `grants_quorum_credit=false` is never counted. Without this, the trust classification is purely aspirational and could be bypassed by a coding error during integration.\n\n---\n\n## SEC-5\n**Severity:** Minor\n**Title:** No specified challenge freshness or expiry allows stale challenge replay within a verification window\n\n**Details:** The plan says the client calls `/api/v1/identity?challenge=<base64>` but does not specify that challenges include a timestamp, are single-use, or expire. The existing endpoint (`api.rs:862-933`) signs whatever challenge is presented with no rate limiting or nonce tracking. If a client reuses a challenge (implementation bug) or an attacker captures a challenge-response pair, the pair remains valid indefinitely because the signed data has no time component. While a fresh 32-byte random challenge per verification mitigates most replays, the plan should be explicit.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add to the plan: (a) challenges MUST be 32 bytes from a CSPRNG, generated fresh for each verification attempt, and MUST NOT be reused; (b) the verifier should discard the challenge immediately after one verification attempt (pass or fail); (c) consider adding a 4-byte Unix timestamp prefix to the challenge that the verifier checks for staleness (e.g., reject if older than 30 seconds), which defends against slow relays even without full channel binding.\n\n---\n\n## SEC-6\n**Severity:** Minor\n**Title:** Race condition between verification failure and target removal allows message leakage\n\n**Details:** The plan mentions \"stale-peer downgrade/removal on verification drift\" (Chunk 3, line 107) but does not describe atomicity. In the current `TransportCoordinator`, targets are selected for Direct tier delivery at `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/coordinator.rs:500-510` by iterating the pool. If a verification refresh fails and triggers removal, but a concurrent `submit_tiered` call has already selected the stale target, the message will be sent to a peer whose identity is no longer verified. This is a TOCTOU race.\n\n**Recommendation:** The plan should specify that target removal uses a two-phase approach: (a) first mark the target as `suspended` (excluded from new target selection), then (b) after a brief drain period (or immediately if no in-flight sends), fully remove it. Alternatively, the plan can note that this is acceptable for v0.4 because Direct tier is best-effort and the message is end-to-end encrypted (only the intended recipient can decrypt), so sending to a wrong peer leaks only metadata (the fact that a message was sent), not content.\n\n---\n\n## SEC-7\n**Severity:** Observation\n**Title:** The `/api/v1/identity` endpoint is behind Basic Auth on the node, which may block LAN discovery\n\n**Details:** In `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/node/src/api.rs:87-98`, the identity endpoint is served through the same router that applies `check_basic_auth` middleware (line 94-97). If the node has Basic Auth configured (which is the recommended production setup), LAN-discovered peers will receive 401 Unauthorized when calling `/api/v1/identity`. The client's embedded HTTP server (`http_server.rs:481-484`) does not have this issue because it has no auth middleware.\n\n**Recommendation:** The plan should note that for node-side identity verification to work, either: (a) the `/api/v1/identity` endpoint must be exempted from Basic Auth (it is safe because it only returns a signature over a caller-provided challenge), or (b) discovered peer probing is limited to client-to-client (which may be the v0.4 intent, but should be stated explicitly).\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe plan's trust classification design is directionally sound -- it correctly identifies the need to separate verified contacts from stranger relays and restricts stranger capabilities. However, three gaps are significant:\n\n1. **SEC-3 (Critical):** The MITM relay attack on the identity challenge-response is the most severe issue. Without channel binding or TLS, a LAN attacker can impersonate any known contact and receive messages intended for them.\n\n2. **SEC-1 and SEC-4 (Major):** Broadcasting stable routing keys creates a passive correlation oracle, and the stranger-relay trust restrictions cannot be enforced by the current transport code without the concrete capability model that Chunk 2 leaves underspecified.\n\n3. The remaining findings (SEC-2, SEC-5, SEC-6, SEC-7) are addressable with plan clarifications rather than architectural changes.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>90756</total_tokens><tool_uses>11</tool_uses><duration_ms>95900</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/872f27a1-9c0c-45e4-b6a3-3674f486326d/tasks/aae66d1624213644c.output",
