          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a26f********22d9</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********PQTk</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/872f27a1-9c0c-45e4-b6a3-3674f486326d/tasks/a26f41827bc9922d9.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Review chunk sequencing & deps\" completed</summary>\n<result>Good -- confirmed the coordinator has no add/remove target methods. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n## Chunk Sequencing and Dependencies Review\n\n### SEQ-1\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** Chunk 2 produces dead code until Chunk 4 lands\n\n**Details:** Chunk 2 adds transport participation categories (send-only direct, stable pollable, relay candidate) and modifies `TransportCoordinator` and `TransportRegistry`. However, the client app at `apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:319` uses `Client<CompositeTransport>`, not `Client<TransportCoordinator>`. The coordinator is not wired into the client until Chunk 4. This means Chunk 2's capability model changes to the coordinator are unreachable from the actual application send/receive path for two full chunks. The receiver polling change (\"only stable mailbox targets are exact-key polled\") is also moot because the client uses `TransportPool` directly for polling (line 321), not the coordinator's `subscribe()`.\n\n**Recommendation:** Merge Chunks 2 and 4 into a single chunk, or reorder so Chunk 4 (migration to coordinator) comes before the capability model. The capability distinctions only matter once the coordinator is actually used. If they must stay separate, Chunk 2 should be framed as a pure library refactor with no runtime-visible effect, and the plan should state that explicitly so reviewers understand the gap.\n\n---\n\n### SEQ-2\n**Severity:** Critical\n**Title:** Chunk 3's discovery controller has no target to register against\n\n**Details:** Chunk 3 says the client discovery controller \"adds/removes only send-only direct targets.\" But at that point in the sequence, the client still uses `CompositeTransport` (Chunk 4 hasn't landed). `CompositeTransport` (`composite.rs:122`) has `add_transport` but no `remove_transport` -- you can add transports but never remove them. The `TransportCoordinator` (`coordinator.rs`) also has no `add_target` or `remove_target` methods; it only accepts pools at construction via `set_http_pool`. The `TransportPool` (`pool.rs:131`) does have `remove_target`, but the discovery controller needs to drive this through the coordinator or some shared handle. As written, the controller literally cannot perform the add/remove lifecycle Chunk 3 specifies.\n\n**Recommendation:** Chunk 3 must depend on both Chunk 2 (capability model) and Chunk 4 (coordinator migration), or Chunk 2 must add `add_target`/`remove_target` methods to `TransportCoordinator` that delegate to the underlying pool. The plan should explicitly state which component owns the target mutation API and ensure it exists before Chunk 3 starts. Suggested order: 1 -> 2+4 (merged) -> 3 -> 5.\n\n---\n\n### SEQ-3\n**Severity:** Minor\n**Title:** Chunk 1 can safely be parallelized with Chunk 2\n\n**Details:** Chunk 1 creates `crates/reme-discovery` with a backend abstraction, TXT helpers, and a fake backend. It has no compile-time dependency on `reme-transport`, `TransportCoordinator`, or the capability model. It depends only on basic types (routing key is a `[u8; 16]` alias) and possibly `reme-identity` for `PublicID`. Chunk 2 modifies the transport layer internally. These two have no shared mutation surface.\n\n**Recommendation:** Mark Chunks 1 and 2 as parallelizable in the plan. If two developers are available, they can proceed simultaneously. Add a note that Chunk 3 is the first integration point requiring both 1 and 2 to be complete.\n\n---\n\n### SEQ-4\n**Severity:** Observation\n**Title:** Node-side work in Chunk 5 is a no-op that could be deferred\n\n**Details:** Chunk 5 says `apps/node`: \"no discovery-specific relay advertisement or acceptance in v0.4.\" The node side of Chunk 5 is literally empty -- the plan itself says there is nothing to do. This is fine as documentation of intent, but it cannot be meaningfully parallelized with earlier chunks because there is no node-side work to parallelize. The client side of Chunk 5 (advertise, browse, auto-register) is the real work and strictly depends on Chunks 1, 2/4, and 3.\n\n**Recommendation:** No reordering needed. Optionally remove the node bullet from Chunk 5 entirely and note in Chunk 6 that node advertisement begins there. This avoids confusion about what Chunk 5 actually delivers.\n\n---\n\n### SEQ-5\n**Severity:** Critical\n**Title:** Chunk 6 depends on infrastructure (relay queue, Tier 3 execution) not built by Chunks 1-5\n\n**Details:** Chunk 6 opens with \"Implement the relay queue and real Tier 3 HTTP relay execution path first.\" This is a major subsystem: the current `TransportCoordinator` (`coordinator.rs:470`) has a comment stub \"Tier 3: Best-Effort (future - BLE, LoRa) / Would add best-effort tier here when implemented.\" The relay queue does not exist anywhere in the codebase. Chunk 6 bundles two very different pieces of work: (a) building the relay queue + Tier 3 execution path from scratch, and (b) wiring discovery into it. The first is a substantial standalone feature that should have its own plan.\n\n**Recommendation:** Either split Chunk 6 into two chunks -- 6a (relay queue + Tier 3 execution path) and 6b (discovery-driven relay use on top of 6a) -- or explicitly state that Chunk 6 has an external dependency on a separate relay-queue implementation plan and cannot start until that plan is complete. The current wording implies Chunk 6 is self-contained, which is misleading for anyone estimating effort or scheduling.\n\n---\n\n### SEQ-6\n**Severity:** Major\n**Title:** Chunk 3 -> Chunk 5 boundary is unclear; Chunk 5 duplicates Chunk 3 scope\n\n**Details:** Chunk 3 says \"adds/removes only send-only direct targets\" and \"implement stale-peer downgrade/removal.\" Chunk 5 says \"auto-register verified contacts as Direct tier peers.\" These appear to describe the same operation. The distinction seems to be that Chunk 3 builds the controller logic and Chunk 5 wires it into the runtime (spawning background tasks, hooking into app startup). But the plan does not make this boundary explicit, creating risk that the implementer of Chunk 3 either builds too much (runtime wiring) or too little (no way to test the controller end-to-end).\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a sentence to Chunk 3 clarifying that it produces a standalone controller with a test harness (using the fake backend from Chunk 1) but no runtime integration. Add to Chunk 5 that it spawns the controller, connects it to the real mDNS backend, and hooks lifecycle events into the TUI. This makes the split testable and reviewable at each boundary.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Recommended Reordering\n\nCurrent: 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 -> 6 -> 7 -> 8\n\nRecommended:\n- **Chunks 1 and 2 in parallel** (no dependency between them).\n- **Merge Chunk 4 into Chunk 2** (or reorder 4 before 3). The coordinator migration must land before the discovery controller can register/remove targets.\n- **Chunk 3 after merged 2+4** (requires both the capability model and the coordinator to be in use).\n- **Chunk 5 after 3** (runtime wiring of the controller).\n- **Split Chunk 6** into relay-queue infrastructure (6a) and discovery-relay integration (6b), or mark 6 as blocked on an external relay-queue plan.\n- **Chunks 7 and 8** are correctly placed at the end and have no hidden dependencies.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>56658</total_tokens><tool_uses>12</tool_uses><duration_ms>76036</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/872f27a1-9c0c-45e4-b6a3-3674f486326d/tasks/a26f41827bc9922d9.output",
