            "content": "# mDNS / LAN Discovery Implementation Plan\n\n> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED: Use `superpowers:subagent-driven-development` (if subagents available) or `superpowers:executing-plans` to implement this plan. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Add the full LAN discovery roadmap in a sequenced way: v0.4 mDNS advertisement/browsing plus verified direct delivery to known contacts, then v0.6 anonymous LAN relay usage on top of the same discovery substrate once the relay queue and real Tier 3 routing exist.\n\n**Architecture:** Build discovery as a shared subsystem for advertisement, browsing, TXT parsing, raw peer snapshots, and identity-probe helpers instead of embedding mDNS logic directly into the client TUI or node bootstrap. Runtime-specific controllers own known-contact matching, trust classification, refresh policy, and transport registration. Transport integration must separate send-only direct peers from fetch-capable stable mailbox targets via a capabilities model orthogonal to the existing `TargetKind` durability axis, and stranger-relay auto-use is deferred until the relay queue and Tier 3 execution path exist.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Rust, Tokio, Axum, existing `/api/v1/identity` HTTP flow, `TransportCoordinator`, `mdns-sd` crate (pure Rust, async-friendly, cross-platform; `zeroconf` as future alternative behind same `DiscoveryBackend` trait), current client embedded HTTP server and standalone node runtime.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n- Scope covers the full discovery substrate plus direct behavior now and relay behavior as a later chunk on the same track:\n  - advertise and browse `_reme._tcp.local`\n  - verify known contacts before using them as direct peers\n  - add relay advertisement, relay acceptance, and stranger-relay auto-use only after relay queue and Tier 3 support exist\n  - keep unknown discovered relays out of quorum, replication, and exact-key fetch\n- Both `apps/client` and `apps/node` participate, but not symmetrically:\n  - client owns known-contact matching and direct delivery\n  - node advertises relay capability and accepts relay ingress\n  - node-side browsing/use of discovered relays is out of scope unless a dedicated relay egress owner is introduced\n- The client send path must migrate from `CompositeTransport` to `TransportCoordinator`, and the TUI send flow must migrate from `send_text()` to `send_text_tiered()` so direct/quorum/best-effort policy is actually enforced. This migration is merged with the transport capability model work (Chunk 2) to avoid dead code.\n- This plan does **not** implement privacy-preserving inbound fetch from untrusted discovered peers. That remains gated on `#27` / `#32`.\n\n## Crate Dependency Diagram\n\n```\nreme-discovery  (new, low-level, NO dependency on reme-transport or reme-identity)\n    ↓ events consumed by\napps/client::discovery_controller  (app-layer glue, depends on reme-discovery + reme-transport + reme-identity)\napps/node::discovery_controller    (app-layer glue, depends on reme-discovery + reme-transport)\n    ↓ mutates targets via\nreme-transport::TransportCoordinator  (single write authority for dynamic targets)\n    ↓ derived read view\nreme-transport::TransportRegistry  (read-only display metadata, no mutation methods)\n```\n\nDiscovery controllers live in the app crates (`apps/client`, `apps/node`), **not** in `reme-discovery`. The `reme-discovery` crate exports only backend-agnostic types (`DiscoveryEvent`, `RawDiscoveredPeer`, `AdvertisementSpec`, `DiscoveryBackend`) with no dependency on `reme-transport` or `reme-identity`.\n\n## Public Interfaces and Config Changes\n\n- Add new shared crate `crates/reme-discovery` with:\n  - `DiscoveryBackend` trait (returns `Result` from `start()`/`bind()` for graceful degradation)\n  - `DiscoveryService`\n  - `AdvertisementSpec`\n  - `DiscoveryEvent` (includes `PeerDiscovered`, `PeerUpdated`, `PeerLost`)\n  - `RawDiscoveredPeer`\n- Keep the `/api/v1/identity` HTTP verification contract in `reme-transport`; discovery controllers call into that existing transport-owned logic rather than duplicating it in `reme-discovery`.\n- Split config ownership cleanly:\n  - client:\n    - `lan_discovery.enabled` default `false` (opt-in for v0.4)\n    - `lan_discovery.advertise` default `true` (when enabled)\n    - `lan_discovery.browse` default `true` (when enabled)\n    - `lan_discovery.refresh_interval_secs` default `300`\n    - `lan_discovery.auto_direct_known_contacts` default `true`\n    - `lan_discovery.bind_interfaces` default `[]` (empty = all interfaces)\n    - `lan_relay.use_discovered_relays` default `false`\n    - `lan_relay.auto_relay_strangers` default `false`\n  - node:\n    - `lan_discovery.enabled` default `false`\n    - `lan_discovery.advertise` default `true` (when enabled)\n    - `lan_discovery.bind_interfaces` default `[]`\n    - `lan_relay.accept_requests` default `false`\n- Add `TargetCapabilities` to transport layer (see Transport Capability Model below).\n- Add coordinator mutation API: `add_http_target()`, `remove_http_target()`, `update_http_target()` delegating to pool methods.\n- Convert `TransportRegistry` to a read-only view over coordinator state: remove `add_http_target()` mutation method, keep only display metadata (labels, tier classification). Coordinator becomes the single write authority.\n- Deprecate and remove `MessageReceiver` -- superseded by `TransportCoordinator::subscribe()`.\n- Add an app/runtime event for newly discovered stranger relays so the UI can later show notification/prompt flows without another architecture pass.\n\n## Transport Capability Model\n\nTwo orthogonal classification axes for targets:\n\n| Axis | Purpose | Values |\n|------|---------|--------|\n| `TargetKind` (existing) | Durability / retry behavior | `Stable`, `Ephemeral` |\n| `TargetCapabilities` (new) | Participation permissions | Bitflags: `SEND`, `FETCH`, `QUORUM_CREDIT`, `REPLICATE` |\n\nComposition examples:\n\n| Target Type | `TargetKind` | Capabilities |\n|-------------|-------------|-------------|\n| Configured mailbox node | `Stable` | `SEND \\| FETCH \\| QUORUM_CREDIT \\| REPLICATE` |\n| Verified discovered contact | `Ephemeral` | `SEND` |\n| Unknown discovered relay (v0.6) | `Ephemeral` | `SEND` (relay-only, no direct) |\n| Manual direct peer (legacy) | `Ephemeral` | `SEND` |\n\nImplementation in `crates/reme-transport/src/target.rs`:\n\n```rust\nbitflags::bitflags! {\n    pub struct TargetCapabilities: u8 {\n        const SEND         = 0b0001;\n        const FETCH        = 0b0010;\n        const QUORUM_CREDIT = 0b0100;\n        const REPLICATE    = 0b1000;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAdd `capabilities: TargetCapabilities` to `TargetConfig`. Default for `Stable` targets: all flags set. Default for `Ephemeral` targets: `SEND` only.\n\nEnforcement points:\n\n- `TransportPool::fetch_once()` and `TransportCoordinator::spawn_http_receiver()`: filter to targets with `FETCH` capability (replaces kind-based filtering).\n- `submit_to_quorum_targets()`: filter to targets with `QUORUM_CREDIT` (replaces `TargetKind::Stable` check).\n- Replication: filter to targets with `REPLICATE`.\n\n## Discovery Contract\n\n- Advertise `_reme._tcp.local`.\n- TXT records are versioned and minimal:\n  - `v=1`\n  - `rk=<routing_key_base64url>` when the peer is direct-addressable\n  - `relay=1` when the peer accepts untrusted best-effort relay ingress\n  - `identity=1` when `/api/v1/identity` is available\n- **Privacy note:** Broadcasting `rk` enables passive LAN presence detection. The routing key is a stable 16-byte `BLAKE3(PublicID)[0..16]` -- any observer can correlate identity presence across sessions. This is an accepted v0.4 trade-off to avoid O(N) verification against all contacts. Future mitigation: rotate `rk` using a session-specific derivative (BLAKE3-KDF with per-boot nonce) that known contacts can resolve. Track in `#TBD`.\n- TXT data is only a hint. Trust comes from verification and local policy.\n- Unknown TXT version (`v=2`, etc.) must be handled gracefully: log a warning, skip the peer, do not crash the TXT parser.\n\n### Identity Verification Flow\n\n- Use advertised `rk` to narrow known contacts.\n- If `rk` matches zero known contacts, **skip the HTTP probe entirely** (do not reveal interest).\n- Call `GET /api/v1/identity?challenge=<base64>` where the challenge is 32 bytes from a CSPRNG, fresh per attempt, discarded immediately after use.\n- **Channel binding (SEC-3 mitigation):** The challenge must include binding material to prevent MITM relay attacks. The signed data becomes: `\"reme-identity-v1:\" || challenge || responder_ip:port || node_pubkey`. The verifier constructs the same `sign_data` using the IP:port it actually connected to. A relayed signature fails because the MITM's IP:port differs from the legitimate peer's. This requires updating `build_identity_sign_data()` in `reme-encryption` and both identity endpoint implementations (node `api.rs`, client `http_server.rs`).\n- **Timing safety (SEC-2 mitigation):** When `rk` narrows to N candidates, always iterate all N and use constant-time comparison for the final pass/fail decision. Do not short-circuit on first match.\n- If one candidate `PublicID` verifies, classify peer as `VerifiedKnownIdentity`.\n- Register the resulting direct target with that verified `PublicID` bound into `TargetConfig::node_pubkey`.\n- Otherwise never promote to direct.\n\n### Stale-Peer Lifecycle\n\n- Verified peers are refreshed periodically (`refresh_interval_secs`) and on transport-level failure.\n- On verification failure: messages are e2e encrypted so content is not leaked, but metadata (that a message was sent) is exposed. Acceptable for v0.4. Mark target as `Suspended` (excluded from new target selection) before removal.\n- The circuit breaker (2 failures for `Ephemeral` targets) provides fast-path removal for abruptly-departed peers. The refresh interval provides the cleanup path. A shorter `stale_time